The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking for example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is an expansion of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in vehicles of the manufacturer.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that is very similar to Nissan’s safety shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bees, able to see in all directions with an angle greater than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, the engineers developed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
This mechanism identifies obstacles that are in front of the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately prevents the collision.
“The moment it detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right angles or greater to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn and not exploiting infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, for this it can work without interruptions and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, and we’re not talking about megabytes.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than lithium-ion batteries.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to the destination avoiding obstacles in the path.
