Morgan Stanley opens its capital at MUFG
Morgan Stanley has entered into an agreement with Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the largest bank in Japan, to invest $9 billion in a 21 percent stake in the company, following a sharp decline in its shares on the stock exchange.
A week after a tentative deal was struck, the two banks said MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s shares at an individual cost of $25.25, or $3 billion.
The fixed price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will also invest $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities at a conversion price of $31.25, ensuring a 10% return.
Morgan Stanley has specified that the global operation would be carried out on the basis of an average price of 29 dollars per share, that is a percentage lower than its current price of 28%.
By 5 p.m., Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% to $23.07.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to a bank holding company,” said John Mack, Morgan Stanley’s chief executive officer.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which is expected to allow it to differentiate its shares but bring them under the control of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms how the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than previously assumed.
The terms defined on Monday also show that in recent days the agreement has been modified: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for a sum of $ 8.5 billion.
A week ago, in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, explained: “We thought that our stake would be exclusively composed of ordinary shares.
But given the current state of the world economy and the market, we have chosen to minimize the risks and protect ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will obtain Morgan Stanley securities at a price below their book value of 7%.
And the deal would result in an investment of at least 20% of equity on a diluted basis.”
The agreement provides that MUFG can convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares in a year if, during a given period, the latter are traded more than 50% below the fixed conversion price, or about $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG would enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to establish a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" lightened its balance sheet from the end of August.
The last few weeks have put a strain on the group, which has seen the value of its shares halved while the cost of risk insurance has skyrocketed.
The cost that ebbed on Monday, however, remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivor" among the big Wall Street investment banks after the collapse of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced that it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
To found the republic on a socialism proper to the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
This was accomplished since, according to the official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, on a basis of votes equal to 80%.
According to these results, the "no" votes were 28%, while 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% blank ballots.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, it would have to get half of the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and an estimate from a non-governmental organization announced a landslide "yes" victory, placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the night between Sunday and Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution has triumphed gloriously," he assured, congratulating Ecuadorians within the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points aimed at consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially from the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently of their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced his intention to take advantage of this amendment and to reapply for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also affirms the gratuitousness of health and education services, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back safe and sound to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at the military base in Almaza, near Cairo International Airport, around 3:30 p.m., aboard a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were immediately transferred, without being able to give any interview to the press, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to be subjected to analysis.
They are in “good health” and no ransom has been paid “to the kidnappers,” Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the airstrip.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari organizing agency.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night, just before dawn.
“There were gunshots, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled,” the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the “lightning” unit were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We must admit that we achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, special forces," he said, without adding any other details.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army said it had intercepted a 4x4 vehicle carrying the kidnappers and had killed six, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and had captured two.
According to the army, the kidnappers are linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the latter.
The Silent Majority of Culture
On the front page there is a debate on the financing of culture, which is the focus of the current election campaign.
So much the better.
But a part of our cultural life is always in the shadows.
Who will speak out to denounce the paltry sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are starving?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government pays three and a half million euros for the restoration of the Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau de Chinon, in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbors, it is the Constitution that affirms that the protection of heritage is part of the national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, by every political authority and by every government department, and all this by mutual agreement.
In Quebec, at the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, there are at least 40 000 volunteers who, grouped in 211 societies for the protection of historical, genealogical, archives and heritage assets preserve, with money, private archives and archaeological sites.
They are the ones who often defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-makers attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are partially nationalising the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to be hit by the crisis in the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial institution - insurance with interests also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, also involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been struggling for more than a year is that of the Fortis bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard may constitute a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the share of the bank in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interest, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week the actions of Fortis had started with a vertical collapse, serious signs of crisis of the institute had appeared then in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank’s shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current share prices, the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The company's top management blamed the collapse of Fortis shares on uncertainties in the non-European market due to the acceptance of the $700 billion U.S. plan.
On Monday, the title slowly picked up.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a meritorious offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they should not be afraid of losing money.
Among the bank’s customers there was no panic, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to take out an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken to the fox," writes the Washington Post quoting Richard Dick, author of the program to follow the prescriptions of the medicines.
Insurance companies make the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of a claim dependent on the health of the customer and do not take out insurance if they consider the risk to be too high.
Some time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only stipulated after the outcome of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer identification code you can easily have information from pharmacies about which medicines he bought in the last year and a half and from this the program shows which diseases he suffers and what health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in the blood is practically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, to the insurer so in addition to paper work there is not much left, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are employable against migraine or hot flashes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the point of view of insurance - commercial, applies as a factor of increased risk, the first two do not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so even though they have so far not imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time controlling the use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of the Congress there is a bill that gives the supervisory authorities competence to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects the forwarding of data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much refuse approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
